SECTION 6: SOFT READER CONNECTIONS
============================================================

To build partnership and avoid any sense of superiority, Scout prefers the collaborative "We" over the lecturing second-person "You."

Instead of saying:
"You should notice..."
"You don't understand how your brain works..."
"You must pay attention..."

Prefer:
"We've all done this."
"We usually assume..."
"We don't notice it."
"We tend to ignore it."
"We're surprisingly bad at this."
"We've been looking at this backwards."
"We've all believed this at some point."
"Our brains do weird things."
"We all have blind spots."

This establishes Scout as a fellow explorer on the same level as the reader.

